  "lessons": [
    {
      "key": "Data Sets",
      "name": "Lesson 1: Data Sets",
      "absolute_position": 1,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can analyzing data sets help us answer questions and solve problems?**\n\nIn this lesson, students learn how to analyze data sets and use that analysis to write algorithms that solve real-world problems. They explore data through charts and tables, asking key questions to uncover insights, then work collaboratively to design and refine algorithms.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the Data Sets Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the Writing Algorithms with Data Sets activity guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can analyzing data sets help us answer questions and solve problems?**\n\nIn this lesson, you learn how to analyze data sets and use that analysis to write algorithms that solve real-world problems. You explore data through charts and tables, asking key questions to uncover insights, then work collaboratively to design and refine algorithms."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Data Sets",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "One-Dimensional (1D) Arrays",
      "name": "Lesson 2: One-Dimensional (1D) Arrays",
      "absolute_position": 2,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I store multiple related values without creating multiple variables?**\n\nStudents have used variables to store literal values and references to objects. In this lesson, students discover the need for one-dimensional (1D) arrays to store multiple related values. Students explore the syntax and functionality of 1D arrays and learn how to declare and initialize a 1D array using the `new` keyword. They learn how to determine the length of a 1D array, then practice creating 1D arrays using the `new` keyword and accessing and returning their length.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the One-Dimensional (1D) Arrays Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the Unit 3 Guide (one for each student)\n* Preview the *One-Dimensional (1D) Arrays* video",
        "student_overview": "**How can I store multiple related values without creating multiple variables?**\n\nYou have used variables to store literal values and references to objects. In this lesson, you discover the need for one-dimensional (1D) arrays to store multiple related values. You explore the syntax and functionality of 1D arrays and learn how to declare and initialize a 1D array using the `new` keyword. You learn how to determine the length of a 1D array then practice creating 1D arrays using the `new` keyword and assigning and accessing values at specific positions."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "One-Dimensional (1D) Arrays",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Modifying Elements",
      "name": "Lesson 3: Modifying Elements",
      "absolute_position": 3,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I easily assign multiple elements to a one-dimensional (1D) array?**\n\nIn this lesson, students explore using initializer lists to create one-dimensional (1D) arrays and learn how to access and modify elements. They discover that the size of a 1D array cannot be changed after it is created and identify similarities and differences between assigning values to a 1D array and to a variable. Students then practice creating a 1D array using initializer lists and modifying the values stored in a 1D array.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the Modifying Elements Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Modifying Values in a 1D Array* video",
        "student_overview": "**How can I easily assign multiple elements to a one-dimensional (1D) array?**\n\nIn this lesson, you explore using initializer lists to create one-dimensional (1D) arrays and learn how to access and modify elements. You discover that the size of a 1D array cannot be changed after it is created and identify similarities and differences between assigning values to a 1D array and to a variable. You then practice creating a 1D array using initializer lists and modifying the values stored in a 1D array."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Modifying Elements",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Traversing 1D Arrays",
      "name": "Lesson 4: Traversing 1D Arrays",
      "absolute_position": 4,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I easily access all elements in a one-dimensional (1D) array?**\n\nStudents have learned how to declare and initialize one-dimensional (1D) arrays and access and modify elements one at a time. In this lesson, students discover the need for loops to repeatedly access multiple elements and revisit `while` loops. Students learn how to traverse 1D arrays using a `while` loop and discover the cause of the `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException` and strategies for debugging this error. Students then practice using `while` loops to traverse one and multiple 1D arrays.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the Traversing 1D Arrays Guided Notes (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can I easily access all elements in a one-dimensional (1D) array?**\n\nYou have learned how to declare and initialize one-dimensional (1D) arrays and access and modify elements one at a time. In this lesson, you discover the need for loops to repeatedly access multiple elements and revisit `while` loops. You learn how to traverse 1D arrays using a `while` loop and discover the cause of the `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException` and strategies for debugging this error. You then practice using `while` loops to traverse one and multiple 1D arrays."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Traversing 1D Arrays",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "For Loops",
      "name": "Lesson 5: For Loops",
      "absolute_position": 5,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I write more efficient code to traverse a 1D array?**\n\nStudents learn about the structure and functionality of a `for` loop and explore how it can be used to traverse a one-dimensional (1D) array. They identify similarities and differences between `while` loops and `for` loops and practice tracing code segments involving a `for` loop to determine the output. Students then practice converting `while` loops to `for` loops and using `for` loops to traverse 1D arrays to access and modify elements and identify ideal scenarios for using each type of loop.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the For Loops Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *For Loops* video",
        "student_overview": "**How can I write more efficient code to traverse a 1D array?**\n\nYou learn about the structure and functionality of a `for` loop and explore how it can be used to traverse a one-dimensional (1D) array. You identify similarities and differences between `while` loops and `for` loops and practice tracing code segments involving a `for` loop to determine the output. You then practice converting `while` loops to `for` loops and using `for` loops to traverse 1D arrays to access and modify elements and identify ideal scenarios for using each type of loop."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "For Loops",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Text Files",
      "name": "Lesson 6: Text Files",
      "absolute_position": 6,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I efficiently read and process data from a file in Java?**\n\nStudents learn to use the `File` class to read data from files and handle file-related exceptions with `throws IOException`. They employ `Scanner` methods to read various data types from a file and use loops to efficiently read and process all file elements. By mastering these techniques, students enhance their ability to manage external data sources and improve their debugging and problem-solving skills in real-world programming scenarios.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the Text Files Guided Notes (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can I efficiently read and process data from a file in Java?**\n\nYou can use the `Scanner` class to read data from a file. In this lesson, you learn to use the `File` class to read data from files and handle file-related exceptions with `throws IOException`. You employ `Scanner` methods to read various data types from a file and use `while` loops to efficiently read and process all file elements. By mastering these techniques, you enhance your ability to manage external data sources and improve your debugging and problem-solving skills in real-world programming scenarios."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Text Files",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Preconditions and Postconditions",
      "name": "Lesson 7: Preconditions and Postconditions",
      "absolute_position": 7,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I perform calculations on the values stored in a 1D array?**\n\nStudents have learned how to create one-dimensional (1D) arrays using the `new` keyword and initializer lists and access and modify one or multiple elements. In this lesson, students read and store values from text files into 1D arrays and consider the preconditions and postconditions an algorithm should satisfy. Students then apply their knowledge of 1D arrays, loops, and returning values from methods to plan and implement algorithms to calculate the sum and average of the values in a 1D array.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the Preconditions and Postconditions Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the CS Bingo Cards (one card for each student)\n* Print the CS Bingo Definitions resource and mix them up OR use [**this web-based version**](https://csabingo.up.railway.app/) to show the terms and definitions\n* Print copies of the Writing Algorithms with Arrays (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can I perform calculations on the values stored in a 1D array?**\n\nYou have learned how to create one-dimensional (1D) arrays using the `new` keyword and initializer lists, how to access and modify one or multiple elements, and how to read and store values from text files. In this lesson, you practice reading and storing values from text files and consider the preconditions and postconditions an algorithm should satisfy. You then apply your knowledge of 1D arrays, loops, and returning values from methods to plan and implement algorithms to calculate the sum and average of the values in a 1D array."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Preconditions and Postconditions",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Ethics in Data",
      "name": "Lesson 8: Ethics in Data",
      "absolute_position": 8,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can biased data impact the fairness and accuracy of a program's outcomes?**\n\nIn this lesson, students consider the ethical and social issues around algorithmic bias and data collection. They learn about algorithmic bias and training data, and the ways algorithmic bias can lead to unfair outcomes. Students analyze data sets in order to identify bias and understand the impact bias has on the conclusions that can be drawn from the data. Finally, students choose a scenario and consider ways in which data can be collected in order to minimize bias.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the Ethical and Social Issues Around Data Collection Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the Analyzing Data Sets handout (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can biased data impact the fairness and accuracy of a program's outcomes?**\n\nIn this lesson, you will consider the ethical and social issues around algorithmic bias and data collection. You will learn about algorithmic bias and training data, and the ways algorithmic bias can lead to unfair outcomes. You will then analyze data sets in order to identify bias and understand the impact bias has on the conclusions that can be drawn from the data. Finally, you will choose a scenario and consider ways in which data can be collected in order to minimize bias."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Ethics in Data",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "(Optional) Polymorphism",
      "name": "Lesson 9: Polymorphism",
      "absolute_position": 9,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can polymorphism improve the efficiency and flexibility of my program code?**\n\nIn this lesson, students expand on what they know about inheritance to explore how they can create arrays of objects. They learn about polymorphism and discover how it can be implemented to make program code more efficient and flexible. Students recall overriding the `toString()` method and how this approach can be applied to override a superclass method in a subclass. Students then practice using superclass references to create and work with 1D arrays.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the Polymorphism Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Polymorphism* video",
        "student_overview": "**How can polymorphism improve the efficiency and flexibility of my program code?**\n\nIn this lesson, you expand on what you know about inheritance to explore how you can create arrays of objects. You learn about polymorphism and discover how it can be implemented to make program code more efficient and flexible. You recall overriding the `toString()` method and how this approach can be applied to override a superclass method in a subclass. You then practice using superclass references to create and work with 1D arrays."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "(Optional) Polymorphism",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Enhanced For Loops",
      "name": "Lesson 10: Enhanced For Loops",
      "absolute_position": 10,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**When would I want to traverse an array with an enhanced `for` loop?**\n\nStudents have learned to use `while` and `for` loops to traverse a 1D array. In this lesson, students explore the syntax and functionality of an enhanced `for` loop and identify scenarios where this type of loop would be useful. Students practice converting `while` and `for` loops to enhanced `for` loops and implementing algorithms to find the sum and average of the values in a 1D array using an enhanced `for` loop.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the Enhanced for Loops Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Careers in Tech: My Name is Polina* and *Enhanced For Loops* videos",
        "student_overview": "**When would I want to traverse an array with an enhanced `for` loop?**\n\nYou have learned to use `while` and `for` loops to traverse a 1D array. In this lesson, you explore the syntax and functionality of an enhanced `for` loop and identify scenarios where this type of loop would be useful. You practice converting `while` and `for` loops to enhanced `for` loops and implementing algorithms to find the sum and average of the values in a 1D array using an enhanced `for` loop."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Enhanced For Loops",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Array Algorithms",
      "name": "Lesson 11: Array Algorithms",
      "absolute_position": 11,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I use what I know about object-oriented programming and 1D arrays to plan and implement algorithms?**\n\nIn this lesson, students apply what they have learned so far to plan and implement standard algorithms to search or modify a one-dimensional (1D) array. Students discover the need for the `equals()` method when comparing `String` objects for equality and explore the difference between executing a return statement inside of a loop and at the end of a method. Students then work with a partner and use manipulatives to plan and implement an algorithm to determine the minimum or maximum value in a 1D array, determine if at least one element in a 1D array has a particular property, determine if all elements in a 1D array have a particular property, or determine the number of elements in a 1D array meet specific criteria. After implementing their algorithm, students conduct a code review to refine and improve their code.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the Array Algorithms Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the Writing Algorithms with Arrays handout (one for each pair of students)\n* Print copies of the Planning Algorithms Manipulatives (one set for each pair of students)\n* (Optional) Cut out the Planning Algorithms Manipulatives and place in baggies",
        "student_overview": "**How can I use what I know about object-oriented programming and 1D arrays to plan and implement algorithms?**\n\nIn this lesson, you apply what you have learned so far to plan and implement standard algorithms to search or modify a one-dimensional (1D) array. You discover the need for the `equals()` method when comparing `String` objects for equality and explore the difference between executing a return statement inside of a loop and at the end of a method. You then work with a partner and use manipulatives to plan and implement an algorithm to determine the minimum or maximum value in a 1D array, determine if at least one element in a 1D array has a particular property, determine if all elements in a 1D array have a particular property, or determine the number of elements in a 1D array meet specific criteria. After implementing your algorithm, you conduct a code review to refine and improve your code."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Array Algorithms",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Finding Duplicates",
      "name": "Lesson 12: Finding Duplicates",
      "absolute_position": 12,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I check if a 1D array contains duplicate elements?**\n\nStudents have learned how to traverse one-dimensional (1D) arrays and implement algorithms to search and modify elements. They expand on their knowledge of loops to explore using nested loops with 1D arrays and practice tracing these to determine the output of code segments using nested loops. Students then work with a partner and use manipulatives to plan and implement an algorithm to find duplicate values in a 1D array.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the Finding Duplicates Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the Finding Duplicates handout (one for each pair of students)\n* Print copies of the Planning Algorithms Manipulatives (one set for each pair of students)\n* (Optional) Cut out the Planning Algorithms Manipulatives and place in baggies\n* Preview the *Nested Loops* video\n* Print copies of the Unit 3 Study Guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can I check if a 1D array contains duplicate elements?**\n\nYou have learned how to traverse one-dimensional (1D) arrays and implement algorithms to search and modify elements. You expand on your knowledge of loops to explore using nested loops with 1D arrays and practice tracing these to determine the output of code segments using nested loops. You then work with a partner and use manipulatives to plan and implement an algorithm to find duplicate values in a 1D array."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Finding Duplicates",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa3-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Data for Social Good Project",
      "name": "Lesson 13a: Data for Social Good Project",
      "absolute_position": 13,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "assessment": true,
        "overview": "**What questions do I want to answer using data?**\n\nFor this project, students use the skills they have developed throughout this unit to store and analyze data from text file for a topic that they are interested in or that is meaningful to them. Students choose a user scenario and data they want to analyze to identify a solution to address a user's needs. After brainstorming and planning, students develop their programs.",
        "preparation": "* Review project setup, requirements, and rubric\n* Print copies of the Data for Social Good Project Planning Guide (one for each student)\n* Create code review groups if you are not reusing the same groups\n* Gather several sticky notes for each student\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-3-10-data-for-social-good-project/37894) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**What questions do I want to answer using data?**\n\nFor this project, you use the skills you have developed throughout this unit to store and analyze data from text files for a topic that you are interested in or that is meaningful to you. You choose a user scenario and data you want to analyze to identify a solution to address a user's needs. After brainstorming and planning, you develop your program."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Data for Social Good Project",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa3-2025"
      }
    },
