  "activity_sections": [
    {
      "key": "96cd609a-ddb8-4b3d-914b-7f262b25d78a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do you notice about this chart? What do you wonder?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should notice key features of the chart, such as the categorization of dogs by intelligence, popularity, and size. They should also begin questioning how the data was collected and what factors influence the placement of different breeds.",
        "name": "The Ultimate Data Dog",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Show the full-size version of the chart so that students can clearly see all the details and labels. This will help them better analyze the data, observe patterns, and ask more informed questions during the discussion. Encourage students to take note of specific categories, data points, and visual elements that stand out to them."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "96cd609a-ddb8-4b3d-914b-7f262b25d78a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "aa24e737-82c7-46b7-b4c4-0bb71cbd3a1a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7524dc0c-2980-4315-88d9-0e11c39bb2b9",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *This is just a snapshot of the data table used to generate the chart. If you were able to see the full data table, what are some specific questions you would be able to answer?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should consider the types of additional insights they could gain from the full data set. They should think about how having more detailed data might allow them to answer specific questions about patterns or rankings that aren't immediately visible in the chart.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Show the full data table that corresponds to the chart so students can see the raw data behind the visual representation. This will help them understand how the chart was generated and encourage deeper analysis by allowing them to connect specific data points with trends or insights they observe in the visual."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7524dc0c-2980-4315-88d9-0e11c39bb2b9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "aa24e737-82c7-46b7-b4c4-0bb71cbd3a1a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2a27ff62-7c26-4073-84fe-5adb5bb66b01",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***data set***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *In looking at this data set, we might ask what the average cost of an item is. We can uncover even more insights by analyzing different aspects of the data. What other questions can we ask about the data in this data set?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should explore various questions that can be asked about the data, such as calculating total revenue, determining the most popular item, or comparing the cost per unit sold across different items.",
        "name": "Writing Algorithms with Data Sets",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to brainstorm as many questions as possible without worrying about the answers initially. You could also group similar questions and guide students to think about how different types of analysis (e.g., averages, totals, trends) could help answer them."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2a27ff62-7c26-4073-84fe-5adb5bb66b01",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a320b2db-449d-4d2e-968c-bf07ccf6d8ec"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f6bb044d-3983-44ea-9540-c912dbe91399",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair a Writing Algorithms with Data Sets activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students review the sample data sets and decide which questions can be answered for each table.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Analyzing different data points in a set can help us solve problems. How might we use data from these examples to answer new questions or uncover trends?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should demonstrate understanding of how analyzing specific data points can reveal patterns or trends. They should think about how data analysis can be used to answer new questions, make decisions, or optimize processes.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***value***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that programmers use data sets to create algorithms to answer questions and solve problems.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *One question we can answer about this data set is: What is the largest value in the \"Units Sold\" column? What would an algorithm need to process this data set and return an accurate answer?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize how algorithms can be used to process data sets, specifically to identify the largest value in a column. They should consider what steps an algorithm would need, such as iterating through the data and comparing values, to find the correct answer.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Walk through the algorithm to find the maximum value.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "As you walk through the algorithm, break it down step by step to ensure students understand the process. Start by explaining the logic behind each step, and highlight key points like like updating the maximum value when a larger value is found. Encourage students to follow along and ask clarifying questions at each step to reinforce their understanding."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f6bb044d-3983-44ea-9540-c912dbe91399",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a320b2db-449d-4d2e-968c-bf07ccf6d8ec"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a88cb07c-f735-4466-a29a-a0bcf8468126",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students choose a data set and a question to answer. They should copy the data table in the space provided on the activity guide, then write pseudocode for an algorithm that will answer that question.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to think about edge cases in the data (e.g., empty data sets, unusually high or low values) while writing their algorithms. This encourages them to write more robust solutions and prepares them for real-world data irregularities."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a88cb07c-f735-4466-a29a-a0bcf8468126",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a320b2db-449d-4d2e-968c-bf07ccf6d8ec"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b10571f8-99d7-45ca-ab46-4057ede90a5c",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share their algorithm with another group and discuss the following prompts:\n* *Does the algorithm use all the needed data to answer the question?*\n* *How can the algorithm be improved to work better or faster?*"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b10571f8-99d7-45ca-ab46-4057ede90a5c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a320b2db-449d-4d2e-968c-bf07ccf6d8ec"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f754dc50-230f-4575-82bb-f16eb918fa48",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *How can charts or tables help you plan your algorithm?*\n* *What challenges did you face while analyzing your data?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should reflect on how charts and tables can simplify data analysis by making patterns or key values easier to identify, which in turn helps in planning algorithms. Students should also share challenges they encountered, such as interpreting data or ensuring accuracy, to promote a deeper understanding of the complexities of data analysis and algorithm design.",
        "name": "Reflection",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f754dc50-230f-4575-82bb-f16eb918fa48",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7a50facc-e879-420f-8553-1b4b2748438d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6132dacf-060a-4dab-95f4-eb8668ac28d7",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 3 Guide includes the Question of the Day and an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to summarize what they have learned and reflect on their progress. Have students respond to these prompts after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and make meaningful connections with the new content."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6132dacf-060a-4dab-95f4-eb8668ac28d7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7a50facc-e879-420f-8553-1b4b2748438d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0282d887-c95b-4a70-9851-ceb09fbf4473",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0282d887-c95b-4a70-9851-ceb09fbf4473",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7a50facc-e879-420f-8553-1b4b2748438d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e5582b5f-1c19-499c-81b6-7cfa89bfeff7",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e5582b5f-1c19-499c-81b6-7cfa89bfeff7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7a50facc-e879-420f-8553-1b4b2748438d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e2537b00-06c4-4c53-b8f6-f419f9cd0f2e",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e2537b00-06c4-4c53-b8f6-f419f9cd0f2e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7a50facc-e879-420f-8553-1b4b2748438d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ed260d2c-409d-4b90-97b3-9eacb854d0bc",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have used variables to store a single value and represent an object's attributes. Software engineers often need to store and process multiple values in their programs.",
        "name": "Storing Multiple Values",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ed260d2c-409d-4b90-97b3-9eacb854d0bc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3c389694-20bd-457c-9ed2-5a0118a661cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a1adbe12-0f6c-42d6-bdf1-6b5db8aa1dde",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How could we store these values in a program based on what we know about Java?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest creating a variable for each value. Students might realize the need for creating a list to store the values and may recall creating lists in programs in previous computer science courses.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class.\n\nAsk students additional probing questions to consider the problems that could arise with maintaining multiple variables. For example:\n* *Is this efficient?*\n* *Is this easy to work with and maintain?*\n* *What would be the ideal way to do this?*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a1adbe12-0f6c-42d6-bdf1-6b5db8aa1dde",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3c389694-20bd-457c-9ed2-5a0118a661cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a0bc9245-8fff-45a9-9bcf-ee4d52bf2596",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a0bc9245-8fff-45a9-9bcf-ee4d52bf2596",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1bd178e9-eb78-41d0-9f94-93e3e5d6e268"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "38a262e3-1138-497d-ba4d-452c507b8079",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "It can be challenging to work with multiple variables in a program. When these are of the same data type and represent the same type of information, there are easier ways to store and work with these values in Java. Today, we're going to learn how we can use one-dimensional arrays to store multiple values.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "38a262e3-1138-497d-ba4d-452c507b8079",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1bd178e9-eb78-41d0-9f94-93e3e5d6e268"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2a807daf-a6db-4ef0-837c-e6649243b316",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Storing Multiple Values"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2a807daf-a6db-4ef0-837c-e6649243b316",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1bd178e9-eb78-41d0-9f94-93e3e5d6e268"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6d449901-faa1-421d-8e2c-8966d78e7467",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that the program declares a variable that is assigned multiple values and the syntax for declaring and initializing the 1D array. Students may wonder what values the 1D array contains or how to assign or access values to the 1D array."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6d449901-faa1-421d-8e2c-8966d78e7467",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1bd178e9-eb78-41d0-9f94-93e3e5d6e268"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4a8fd40f-6c90-4be0-9c52-7419371b12bc",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When we want to work with multiple related values, we can use a one-dimensional, or 1D, array to store these. A 1D array allows us to reference these values with just one variable.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Exploring 1D Arrays",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4a8fd40f-6c90-4be0-9c52-7419371b12bc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1bd178e9-eb78-41d0-9f94-93e3e5d6e268"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "26a50e2f-1d8b-41d0-8c4a-2fe5a45b1ea2",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *One-Dimensional (1D) Arrays*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "26a50e2f-1d8b-41d0-8c4a-2fe5a45b1ea2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1bd178e9-eb78-41d0-9f94-93e3e5d6e268"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5510a253-f899-4d40-8385-56d20fa2f571",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define **data structure** and **one-dimensional array**.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain that data structures contain zero or more elements and define ***element***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: 1D Arrays"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5510a253-f899-4d40-8385-56d20fa2f571",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1bd178e9-eb78-41d0-9f94-93e3e5d6e268"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ebd75ba5-debd-4af7-a748-1f7af32073e7",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ebd75ba5-debd-4af7-a748-1f7af32073e7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1bd178e9-eb78-41d0-9f94-93e3e5d6e268"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fe1cb3d0-13d3-4faf-b3b4-87a7a9bc0c26",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When arrays are created, each element is automatically given a default value. Understanding these values—and how to find the length of an array—helps programmers write code that works reliably with any array.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Default Values and Length",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fe1cb3d0-13d3-4faf-b3b4-87a7a9bc0c26",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1bd178e9-eb78-41d0-9f94-93e3e5d6e268"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5c6d0cd3-0bac-4cd0-983e-484688499b26",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Explain how 1D arrays are declared and initialized:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Declaring a 1D array\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Initializing a 1D array\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Declaring and initializing a 1D array in one line\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain that a 1D array is an object and is accessed using a reference variable.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Prompt students to recall the meaning of a reference variable and how it is different from a primitive variable."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5c6d0cd3-0bac-4cd0-983e-484688499b26",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1bd178e9-eb78-41d0-9f94-93e3e5d6e268"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "12c9b138-9d90-4a90-ad9e-13d079ea7c87",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Click through the animated slides to demonstrate the default values that get stored in a 1D array when it is declared and initialized using the `new` keyword:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Array of `int` values\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Array of `double` values\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Array of `boolean` values\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Array of `String` values",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Prompt students to recall the default values for each data type before showing the values.\n\nStudents will learn about storing objects in 1D arrays in an upcoming lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "12c9b138-9d90-4a90-ad9e-13d079ea7c87",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1bd178e9-eb78-41d0-9f94-93e3e5d6e268"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c90c499d-ebc3-429a-9ba6-b3125d6d14fe",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Explain how to determine the length of a 1D array:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The length of a 1D array is how many elements it can store.\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Introduce the syntax for accessing the length of a 1D array.\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The length of a 1D array is one more than the last index."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c90c499d-ebc3-429a-9ba6-b3125d6d14fe",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1bd178e9-eb78-41d0-9f94-93e3e5d6e268"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "baaf9014-559c-4a4d-be71-dbdafb22e1d6",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Many of the apps and programs we use every day use large amounts of data to help us find information we are looking for, perform calculations, or recommend similar videos or products. 1D arrays give software engineers a way to store and analyze large amounts of data.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Creating 1D Arrays",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "baaf9014-559c-4a4d-be71-dbdafb22e1d6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1bd178e9-eb78-41d0-9f94-93e3e5d6e268"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "85346493-f669-44f5-a420-6d01685052cf",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce how arrays are useful for storing and analyzing data.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The table on the slide shows a snippet of the [**Music & Mental Health Survey Results**](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/catherinerasgaitis/mxmh-survey-results) dataset on Kaggle. Students will have opportunities to work with this and other datasets throughout the unit to practice creating 1D arrays and writing standard algorithms to find information, perform manipulations, and identify trends in preparation for the Data for Social Good Project during the Show What You Know week. You may show the full dataset on Kaggle and have students consider questions they could answer about this dataset and what problems they could solve based on information they could discover."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "85346493-f669-44f5-a420-6d01685052cf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1bd178e9-eb78-41d0-9f94-93e3e5d6e268"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3b65d6eb-2b15-41e7-ae40-d1546684b13c",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***data abstraction***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5, 6, and 7. Students complete a Check for Understanding, then continue to Level 6 to complete a choice level to return the length of a 1D array from a class. On Level 7, students complete a choice level to declare and initialize a 1D array.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Creating 1D Arrays",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice level can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of the key terms, creating 1D arrays using the new keyword, and accessing the length of a 1D array."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3b65d6eb-2b15-41e7-ae40-d1546684b13c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1bd178e9-eb78-41d0-9f94-93e3e5d6e268"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1a55988e-c328-4c3e-9f7e-d1f159563d45",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are some physical examples that are similar to a 1D array?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest physical items that can store multiple items, such as a storage facility, school lockers, or a bike rack.",
        "name": "Physical Arrays",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1a55988e-c328-4c3e-9f7e-d1f159563d45",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8ee17f59-7e5c-46a2-a667-2957e990dd4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b9717222-b9aa-4294-8c1a-8fe46f807df3",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
