    {
      "key": "c36213a4-7271-485a-b28f-6dbec7f510a4",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Software engineers often work with very large amounts of data. When working with larger amounts of data, storing information in arrays is not as practical. ",
        "name": "Too Much Data",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c36213a4-7271-485a-b28f-6dbec7f510a4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d804998c-1006-4035-a964-13cefb72118a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a9e0a381-1dd0-4ea2-b7cb-9264d1e6218a",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *We have learned to work with 1D arrays. Imagine you had hundreds of lines of data. How might processing this data in an array become challenging?*\n* *What are some potential problems with storing large amounts of data directly in an array?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** The goal of this discussion is to help students recognize the limitations of using 1D arrays for handling large datasets. By the end of the discussion, students should identify challenges related to memory, efficiency, and code complexity. Students should leave the discussion with questions about what more advanced data structures might look like. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a9e0a381-1dd0-4ea2-b7cb-9264d1e6218a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d804998c-1006-4035-a964-13cefb72118a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e13c5a1f-75fe-4991-8fd4-8ab13810b228",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e13c5a1f-75fe-4991-8fd4-8ab13810b228",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b07f9ed2-f5b3-4832-8007-103db9399d69"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0d5240e1-fa47-412f-9c21-deac2d1326f4",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You have probably gotten user input in other programming languages. In Java, we use the `Scanner` class to get user input from the keyboard, but we also use the `Scanner` class to read text from a file. In this lesson, we will learn how to set up the `File` and `Scanner` classes to read text from a file, and how to use while loops to read multiple lines of data from a file efficiently. ",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0d5240e1-fa47-412f-9c21-deac2d1326f4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b07f9ed2-f5b3-4832-8007-103db9399d69"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "df97c583-4377-42bc-b40b-58a87af5cd3e",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Reading Text Files"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "df97c583-4377-42bc-b40b-58a87af5cd3e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b07f9ed2-f5b3-4832-8007-103db9399d69"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "55a9f49e-424a-4f2a-ad38-b0f9c12dde3f",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What do you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that values are stored in a text file and read into the program. Students also notice that the first line of the text file is used to create a `Student` object. Students may wonder how to read multiple lines of data or how to read different types of data."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "55a9f49e-424a-4f2a-ad38-b0f9c12dde3f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b07f9ed2-f5b3-4832-8007-103db9399d69"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a962cc2a-abfa-4d67-94a3-4e82821ead2e",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***file*** and explain that the contents of a file can be accessed by a program.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***text file***.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Reading and Processing Text Files",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask students if they have used a text editor such as Notepad. Have students identify the similarities and differences between the files created in these text editors and programs like Microsoft Word or Google Docs."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a962cc2a-abfa-4d67-94a3-4e82821ead2e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b07f9ed2-f5b3-4832-8007-103db9399d69"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "97985a9e-db05-4fbd-8b1f-3c8860750886",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the `File` class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that the `File` class needs to be imported and briefly introduce the `File` class constructors.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How can reading a text file be useful in a program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students note that a program can read data in a file. Students may also suggest that it makes the program more user-friendly and adaptable. The user does not need to enter the files directly into the array, and one program can process multiple data sets.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to investigate the program with a partner. Students make the changes to the program as prompted.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Reading Text Files"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "97985a9e-db05-4fbd-8b1f-3c8860750886",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b07f9ed2-f5b3-4832-8007-103db9399d69"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d78b70f8-0661-4dec-8c63-135bdc50087d",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the libraries that must be imported into the class where the file reading method is being written.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that the `java.io.IOException` library must be imported in the tester class and the class where the file reader method is being written.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain how to validate the file name being used by adding `throws IOException` to the header of the method that uses the file. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain how to create a `File` object and `Scanner` object to read the file being processed by the method. Remind students to call the `close()` method after the `Scanner` is finished reading from the file.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the `split()` method and explain how it can be used to split text into an array of `String` objects.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to show students the various `Scanner` methods that they may need to process a file.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 3 on Code Studio to investigate the program with a partner. Students make the changes to the program as prompted.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Processing File Data"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d78b70f8-0661-4dec-8c63-135bdc50087d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b07f9ed2-f5b3-4832-8007-103db9399d69"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d3acc800-c7d4-4835-9aa5-2ba0e6b6327f",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain how to use a `while` loop and the `hasNext()` method to detect if the file still contains elements to read.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain how to implement a standard algorithm students may have seen when traversing arrays within a file reading method. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d3acc800-c7d4-4835-9aa5-2ba0e6b6327f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b07f9ed2-f5b3-4832-8007-103db9399d69"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c6d7436a-49d3-4f7e-9152-e7b91cf84112",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Reading a text file may seem complicated at first, so it is important to practice writing methods that open and read from text files. Another part of this practice is learning how to process lines from the text file in a meaningful way. ",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Reading Text Files",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c6d7436a-49d3-4f7e-9152-e7b91cf84112",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b07f9ed2-f5b3-4832-8007-103db9399d69"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "921d22d4-6453-4da5-a187-8cbf0c90185f",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 4 on Code Studio to complete a choice level to read and process a text file. ",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Reading Text Files",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The practice level can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of reading and processing text files."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "921d22d4-6453-4da5-a187-8cbf0c90185f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b07f9ed2-f5b3-4832-8007-103db9399d69"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "eac4836b-2364-4c7b-bbbe-d1a89b0d7eaf",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We’ve now seen how the `Scanner` and `File` classes can be used to read and process text files. We’ve also seen how to use `while` loops to process the data from a text file efficiently, and to apply standard algorithms to that data. Depending on the needs of our programs, we may need to process the data from a text file in a variety of ways. ",
        "name": "Closing the Loop",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "eac4836b-2364-4c7b-bbbe-d1a89b0d7eaf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b68c1ffc-10b4-425b-ac1a-e6bc6d8b80b4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "42b034fa-b098-4ab7-b127-9d53bb587c9a",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What are the key takeaways of this lesson?*\n* *Which parts of this lesson built off of previous lesson content? Which parts are completely new?*\n* *What words would you use to describe our learning as a class today?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Some key takeaways students might point out are the syntax of the code segments for using the `File` and `Scanner` classes to read from a text file. Students may also recall that three libraries need to be imported into their file in order to read from a text file. Some may also mention that reading from a text file and processing its data is similar to what they have learned about processing the data from an array.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "42b034fa-b098-4ab7-b127-9d53bb587c9a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b68c1ffc-10b4-425b-ac1a-e6bc6d8b80b4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a848ab6a-0d49-43ce-8b7a-5651df893d59",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a848ab6a-0d49-43ce-8b7a-5651df893d59",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b68c1ffc-10b4-425b-ac1a-e6bc6d8b80b4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b7cd2b1e-0ce7-4f40-b577-4175e8b69fb9",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b7cd2b1e-0ce7-4f40-b577-4175e8b69fb9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b68c1ffc-10b4-425b-ac1a-e6bc6d8b80b4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "25c1d1d2-518b-4b3f-93fd-45cbbdadb28f",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned a lot of new terms so far! Let's review some of these terms through a game of CS Bingo.",
        "name": "CS Bingo",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "25c1d1d2-518b-4b3f-93fd-45cbbdadb28f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "80a20abb-d9b8-4407-b469-fc77f3c9f508"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "98c8eee8-de99-40ff-8dd5-8ef88f6dd49f",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a unique CS Bingo Card.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the instructions for playing CS Bingo.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Play the music clip to cue the CS Bingo activity. Choose a random definition and read it aloud to the class. Give students a moment to check their bingo card for the correct term, then state the correct term. Repeat until a student yells \"Java.\"",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "To allow for multiple students to \"win\" the game, continue pulling definitions until a couple more students win as well."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "98c8eee8-de99-40ff-8dd5-8ef88f6dd49f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "80a20abb-d9b8-4407-b469-fc77f3c9f508"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "69c43caf-2d06-4c59-82f2-8a368237c7d3",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "69c43caf-2d06-4c59-82f2-8a368237c7d3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "308cf2e4-641f-45de-9dab-3c36614e2ca2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c2e95076-6640-48bb-b8ca-2bc492c87798",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "As software engineers work with larger amounts of data, they often need to store the information in other files to read into their programs.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c2e95076-6640-48bb-b8ca-2bc492c87798",
        "lesson_activity.key": "308cf2e4-641f-45de-9dab-3c36614e2ca2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0cb4e49f-bdb0-42f7-a8ae-2bf0e30ed7a2",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Reading a File"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0cb4e49f-bdb0-42f7-a8ae-2bf0e30ed7a2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "308cf2e4-641f-45de-9dab-3c36614e2ca2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ff07702a-aff4-4d8b-ac59-4f0a5cb11afa",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that values are stored in a text file and read into the program. Students also notice that the values are stored in a 1D array. Students may wonder how they might work with larger files or with multiple types of values or how they could write data to a file."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ff07702a-aff4-4d8b-ac59-4f0a5cb11afa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "308cf2e4-641f-45de-9dab-3c36614e2ca2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4ddbcf02-e192-44d9-b65f-83802686eeca",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When software engineers plan an algorithm, they take into consideration things that must be true for the algorithm to work and things that must be true after the algorithm finishes. This helps us to decide if we need to check for things like invalid values before executing the algorithm so we don't have unexpected results or errors.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Preconditions and Postconditions",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4ddbcf02-e192-44d9-b65f-83802686eeca",
        "lesson_activity.key": "308cf2e4-641f-45de-9dab-3c36614e2ca2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "68f06b9c-509d-4cc0-8bce-cb61c15f8759",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Click through the animated slides to explain the functionality of non-void methods with parameters:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Can receive values through parameters\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Use those values\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Return a computed value of the specified type\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***precondition***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***postcondition***.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Point out how the precondition and postcondition for the code segment are noted in the method comment. Emphasize to students about indicating these in the comments to provide documentation about the purpose and functionality of a method.\n\nAsk students to consider whether these preconditions and postconditions are currently being satisfied in the example code segment. Have students share ideas for how to improve the code segment to satisfy these conditions."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "68f06b9c-509d-4cc0-8bce-cb61c15f8759",
        "lesson_activity.key": "308cf2e4-641f-45de-9dab-3c36614e2ca2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3d159b3a-9953-477a-9074-6608fe3cb794",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What scenarios or tasks have you encountered that have preconditions or postconditions? Why do those matter?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest scenarios that have preconditions, such as making sure they have enough money before buying an item. Students share postconditions for the scenarios they suggest, such as obtaining the item and the amount of money they have decreasing by the price of the item. Students note how these preconditions and postconditions matter in the scenarios they share, such as ensuring that someone can't obtain an item if they don't have enough money or ensuring that someone's balance decreases by the correct amount after they purchase an item.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3d159b3a-9953-477a-9074-6608fe3cb794",
        "lesson_activity.key": "308cf2e4-641f-45de-9dab-3c36614e2ca2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "62e30310-0f9b-440a-9d04-b805554d7427",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Consider this scenario. What would be the precondition for this algorithm? What would be the postcondition?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest preconditions for the algorithm, such as making sure that the 1D array contains valid values. Students also suggest postconditions for the algorithm, such as that the !D array is not modified and that the correct result is returned.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students struggle to identify preconditions and postconditions for the algorithm, ask additional probing questions to help them determine conditions that must be true before and after the algorithm executes. For example:\n* *Should this algorithm be applied to an empty array?*\n* *Should this algorithm only work for certain data types?*\n* *Should this algorithm make changes to the array?*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "62e30310-0f9b-440a-9d04-b805554d7427",
        "lesson_activity.key": "308cf2e4-641f-45de-9dab-3c36614e2ca2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "41994005-fab2-4b5e-a268-8be1f057883c",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Preconditions and postconditions are useful for identifying what conditions must be met for a method to execute as intended and the expected outcome. Software engineers write method code to satisfy the postconditions when preconditions are met.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "41994005-fab2-4b5e-a268-8be1f057883c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "308cf2e4-641f-45de-9dab-3c36614e2ca2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "20744dc2-ca58-4d43-86e4-28e38d838006",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Consider this method. What should we add or modify to make sure the preconditions are met so we can satisfy the postconditions?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest adding an `if` statement to check if the array contains valid values and returning an unexpected result such as `-1` to indicate to the user that the array is invalid.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate a solution."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "20744dc2-ca58-4d43-86e4-28e38d838006",
        "lesson_activity.key": "308cf2e4-641f-45de-9dab-3c36614e2ca2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "17fa93d8-b76b-4a78-97bb-f88c9078c097",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "As you plan algorithms, you should take a moment to identify and note the preconditions and postconditions of the algorithm. Your algorithms should make sure that the preconditions are satisfied so that the algorithm executes without errors or unexpected results. This is how software engineers make sure their programs don't crash and improve the user experience.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Writing Algorithms with Arrays",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "17fa93d8-b76b-4a78-97bb-f88c9078c097",
        "lesson_activity.key": "308cf2e4-641f-45de-9dab-3c36614e2ca2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "13411af0-e366-49e7-8da0-b7a8653d189e",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Writing Algorithms with Arrays handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to choose a scenario and write pseudocode for an algorithm to find the sum and average of all values in a 1D array.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students complete a Check for Understanding, then continue to Level 3 to complete a choice level to implement their algorithm to find the sum of all values in a 1D array. On Level 4, students complete a choice level to implement their algorithm to find the average of all values in a 1D array.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Writing Algorithms with Arrays",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice level can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of the key terms and writing algorithms with 1D arrays."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "13411af0-e366-49e7-8da0-b7a8653d189e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "308cf2e4-641f-45de-9dab-3c36614e2ca2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "88c603d7-9ae1-4466-920f-8de9b1acf3a0",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Congratulations! You've written your first standard algorithms using 1D arrays! Software engineers write these types of algorithms all the time, and these are useful for a variety of scenarios.",
        "name": "Glows, Grows, Want-to-Knows",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "88c603d7-9ae1-4466-920f-8de9b1acf3a0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ed6fa910-f1d2-41b6-9b79-b28ba491a671"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9e676b1b-723e-4043-8128-8864c2981ced",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What was awesome about writing your code?*\n* *What is one action you can take to improve your code?*\n* *What questions do you have about today?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share their highlights and achievements they experienced while planning and implementing their algorithms as well as bugs or struggles they had and how they overcame these. Students might share ideas for ways to improve their code, such as identifying and checking for additional preconditions or adding another method to return a message if the preconditions were not met. Students may share questions they might have based on their experience implementing their algorithms.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Glows, Grows, Want-to-Knows is a strategy to help students identify their strengths and areas of improvement and share any questions or misconceptions."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9e676b1b-723e-4043-8128-8864c2981ced",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ed6fa910-f1d2-41b6-9b79-b28ba491a671"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "92d76709-833a-4f80-91b0-b4fae3aaaccb",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 3 Guide includes the Question of the Day and an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to summarize what they have learned and reflect on their progress. Have students respond to these prompts after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and make meaningful connections with the new content."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "92d76709-833a-4f80-91b0-b4fae3aaaccb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ed6fa910-f1d2-41b6-9b79-b28ba491a671"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2bc4a5aa-a8d5-4fd6-8d0b-1e81242743fa",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
