      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5af790bd-4442-4152-8d7e-c23f21f3f2b6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In this lesson we will explore why data sets need to represent all scenarios and user groups. Throughout the lesson, consider how a data set that lacks representation of all scenarios and user groups would affect a system’s fairness and effectiveness.",
        "name": "Representation on Data Sets",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5af790bd-4442-4152-8d7e-c23f21f3f2b6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6d9cfe94-3f98-40fc-9347-8e18d96ac842"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "46f9f0e0-2655-4fed-8224-830b5917dc4b",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *Is it important for a data set to represent all possible scenarios and user groups? Why or why not?*\n* *If a facial recognition data set mainly includes one ethnicity, how might this impact the system's effectiveness and fairness?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize the importance of diversity in data sets and understand that if a facial recognition system is trained on a data set that primarily includes one ethnicity, it may result in biased outcomes. They would discuss how this could lead to less effective systems that are unfair to other ethnicities."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "46f9f0e0-2655-4fed-8224-830b5917dc4b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6d9cfe94-3f98-40fc-9347-8e18d96ac842"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3c6e2549-fb28-45f8-82a6-a21d3adbd199",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Training Data and Algorithmic Bias"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3c6e2549-fb28-45f8-82a6-a21d3adbd199",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a2ffa70d-bfde-422d-8d5f-abf374659393"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "64748908-7044-4f87-a982-71c9443ba8a6",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We will start by exploring how biased data affects the fairness and accuracy of program outcomes. ",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "64748908-7044-4f87-a982-71c9443ba8a6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a2ffa70d-bfde-422d-8d5f-abf374659393"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "43ef7d82-6c9b-448a-a031-f650c58e3b49",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***algorithmic bias***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video - *Training Data & Bias*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Depending on how training data is collected, who is doing the collecting, and how the data is fed, there is a chance that human bias is included in the data. What steps can be taken to ensure that the data collected for training a machine learning model is comprehensive and unbiased?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students brainstorm and discuss steps to ensure that machine learning training data is comprehensive and unbiased. Students may mention using diverse data sets, checking data sets for inherent bias, and ways to check for possible biases during data collection. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "43ef7d82-6c9b-448a-a031-f650c58e3b49",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a2ffa70d-bfde-422d-8d5f-abf374659393"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4a75b967-2fe6-479c-93ff-de489b3ec744",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4a75b967-2fe6-479c-93ff-de489b3ec744",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a2ffa70d-bfde-422d-8d5f-abf374659393"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2473b627-f6ed-4a89-b6ff-ca95e0db3fe2",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *The video mentions that if X-ray data is only collected from men, the predictions might not work for women. How does this example illustrate the concept of algorithmic bias?*\n* *What are some other real-world examples where incomplete data could lead to unfair outcomes?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students brainstorm and discuss steps to ensure that machine learning training data is comprehensive and unbiased. Students may mention using diverse data sets, checking data sets for inherent bias, and ways to check for possible biases during data collection.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class.\n\nPrompt students to consider real-world examples they have heard of, or to speculate about ways that biased data could lead to unfair outcomes."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2473b627-f6ed-4a89-b6ff-ca95e0db3fe2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a2ffa70d-bfde-422d-8d5f-abf374659393"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0503656d-7104-4c72-9002-b0441e47db2c",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0503656d-7104-4c72-9002-b0441e47db2c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a2ffa70d-bfde-422d-8d5f-abf374659393"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f92a2470-1ab9-4b41-ab03-82c201b30a25",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now let's explore how to evaluate data sets for bias, and how to design methods for data collection to ensure fairness. You’ll start by looking at an existing data set and trying to spot both where the data set may show bias, and how that bias skews the answers to questions we might ask. Your goal is to identify potential issues and think about strategies to address these biases in your own data collection methods.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Analyzing Data Sets",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f92a2470-1ab9-4b41-ab03-82c201b30a25",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a2ffa70d-bfde-422d-8d5f-abf374659393"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2ab820fb-31ef-4073-bd12-80ce5ba635a9",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Analyzing Data Sets handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Lesson 8, Level 1 on Code Studio. Have them choose a data set to review and complete Part 1 of the activity guide for the selected data set.",
        "progression_name": "Data Sets",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to ask critical questions about representation and completeness in their chosen data set. As they work through the handout, prompt them to consider which groups are included and which are excluded. Encourage students to speculate about real-world examples that would illustrate how bias can impact decisions made from the data."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2ab820fb-31ef-4073-bd12-80ce5ba635a9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a2ffa70d-bfde-422d-8d5f-abf374659393"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "314574a8-5886-47fd-8006-679ce9825107",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "314574a8-5886-47fd-8006-679ce9825107",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a2ffa70d-bfde-422d-8d5f-abf374659393"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "45d65d7c-699a-4677-b402-a0dfe7ec311d",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to choose a scenario from Part II of the \"Analyzing Data Sets\" activity guide. They review the goals they want to achieve with the data they will collect and consider how to minimize bias and ensure their approach accurately represents all perspectives. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to form groups and share their approaches. Students should discuss the potential biases in the data they plan to collect and the way it is collected, and the ways in which those biases can be minimized. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *It may not be possible to eliminate all forms of bias from a data set, but efforts can be made to reduce potential biases. Based on your methodology and the methodology of other groups, how can bias be minimized?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students surface specific strategies that they noticed in their own methodology and the methodologies of other groups. They discuss how these strategies can be applied across different scenarios in order to achieve more accurate and representative results. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "45d65d7c-699a-4677-b402-a0dfe7ec311d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a2ffa70d-bfde-422d-8d5f-abf374659393"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6fa6987a-ee72-44e8-a92a-0ab44843fb77",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In this lesson, we focused on evaluating data sets for bias and designing methods to ensure fairness in data collection. Accurate and complete data sets are crucial for reliable results and fairness.",
        "name": "Closing the Loop",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6fa6987a-ee72-44e8-a92a-0ab44843fb77",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1c9551a6-94a5-4655-b234-7701adb4d8f5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bc980d7a-d393-4cae-a15c-25b513335a51",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *Why is it important to use accurate and complete data sets?*\n* *What are the potential consequences of using biased or incomplete data?*\n* *How can we ensure our data sets are relevant to the questions we want to answer?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students will be able to explain the significance of using accurate and complete data sets. Students will also speculate on real-world examples of consequences from using biased or incomplete data.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bc980d7a-d393-4cae-a15c-25b513335a51",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1c9551a6-94a5-4655-b234-7701adb4d8f5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "aab4f352-35bf-451d-8cc9-f5ffc58af623",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "aab4f352-35bf-451d-8cc9-f5ffc58af623",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1c9551a6-94a5-4655-b234-7701adb4d8f5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a7d9e4f0-fc28-4d2d-a3e7-8a4d4c3bf24b",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a7d9e4f0-fc28-4d2d-a3e7-8a4d4c3bf24b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1c9551a6-94a5-4655-b234-7701adb4d8f5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "14a2d4c1-fd53-447f-8e1f-e555743d7853",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Each food truck at Joyful Pastries sells a variety of desserts. The owner needs a way to quickly determine what desserts each food truck offers and apply discounts based on the specific type of dessert.",
        "name": "Solve the Problem",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "14a2d4c1-fd53-447f-8e1f-e555743d7853",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3e767c46-a6b1-4e51-9543-ed3d99dd1ee3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2244ead9-650e-4203-bc91-c77a9a61c80f",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Review inheritance:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Definition of inheritance\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Purpose and functionality of the superclass\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Purpose and functionality of a subclass\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Inheritance is an is-a relationship\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Joyful Pastries problem and classes.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How could we organize and work with the desserts offered at each food truck using 1D arrays?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest solutions for organizing the desserts into 1D arrays. Students may suggest creating an array for each type of `Dessert` or creating a single array that is of type `Dessert` that can store the different types of desserts.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask students to consider the benefits and drawbacks of their solutions. For example, if students suggest creating arrays for each type of `Dessert`, ask students about the efficiency and maintainability of this approach. If students suggest creating a single `Dessert` array, ask students how they would refer to a method to apply a discount differently for each type of dessert. Encourage students to recall how the `toString()` method was overridden and how overriding a method might be helpful in this scenario."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2244ead9-650e-4203-bc91-c77a9a61c80f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3e767c46-a6b1-4e51-9543-ed3d99dd1ee3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6385a7ce-2d94-44d7-8b79-ae3d76a7f44d",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6385a7ce-2d94-44d7-8b79-ae3d76a7f44d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c08ddab8-bdd7-438d-bcc6-0999d74814e2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b23fdf05-6460-4244-9d8e-020611d310cd",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned how to use 1D arrays to store `int`, `double`, or `String` values, which has been useful for working with multiple related values. We can also create 1D arrays to store references to multiple related objects and use an object-oriented programming principle known as polymorphism. Today, we're going to learn how we can create and work with 1D arrays that store references to objects and how polymorphism can make our 1D arrays, classes, and methods more flexible.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b23fdf05-6460-4244-9d8e-020611d310cd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c08ddab8-bdd7-438d-bcc6-0999d74814e2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "882dc9fa-1ecd-4709-94c1-f0273a973db0",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Polymorphism"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "882dc9fa-1ecd-4709-94c1-f0273a973db0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c08ddab8-bdd7-438d-bcc6-0999d74814e2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "809737f3-167a-4178-a11c-2a9b920a0232",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that the 1D array stores references to objects and that they can call an object's method while traversing the array. Students may wonder how they could create an array of different types of objects that extend the same superclass and whether calling each object's method will call the subclass version while traversing the array."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "809737f3-167a-4178-a11c-2a9b920a0232",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c08ddab8-bdd7-438d-bcc6-0999d74814e2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8cdba116-668e-4b4c-b95f-fd82497df9ed",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Inheritance allows us to create superclasses that have attributes and behaviors that can be shared with subclasses. The subclasses we create are more specific versions of the superclass, and they each have a is-a relationship with the superclass. This means we can declare reference variables of the superclass type that point to objects of a subclass type. Let's take a look at how this works.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Polymorphism",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8cdba116-668e-4b4c-b95f-fd82497df9ed",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c08ddab8-bdd7-438d-bcc6-0999d74814e2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c89b2b16-d4ec-4fbd-b908-a6f6d7659258",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Polymorphism"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c89b2b16-d4ec-4fbd-b908-a6f6d7659258",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c08ddab8-bdd7-438d-bcc6-0999d74814e2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "de021d78-f0fe-4836-a6d4-95ec3dc46a92",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "de021d78-f0fe-4836-a6d4-95ec3dc46a92",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c08ddab8-bdd7-438d-bcc6-0999d74814e2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2470ca3a-eb03-4767-a8d5-53b3ecdd0daa",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Polymorphism*.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Overriding Methods",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2470ca3a-eb03-4767-a8d5-53b3ecdd0daa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c08ddab8-bdd7-438d-bcc6-0999d74814e2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0f640aae-234f-4f0e-9cc9-8f545efc8d42",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***polymorphism***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do you recall about overriding a method?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recall overriding the `toString()` method in a class so it can return a `String` containing information about an object instead of what is returned in the `Object` class version of the method.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0f640aae-234f-4f0e-9cc9-8f545efc8d42",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c08ddab8-bdd7-438d-bcc6-0999d74814e2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5392bf28-8227-4f7f-81c6-e50192454544",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Recall overriding.\n\n**Do This:** Explain overriding methods in a subclass:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Each class has a method that performs a similar behavior\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Subclass can override the superclass version of the method\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Calling the method on an object of a superclass type calls its version of the method\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Calling the method on an object of a subclass type calls its version of the method",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Point out that when the code is compiled, Java checks that the method exists in either the superclass or subclass. When the code is run, Java uses the method in the subclass if it exists or the method in the superclass."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5392bf28-8227-4f7f-81c6-e50192454544",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c08ddab8-bdd7-438d-bcc6-0999d74814e2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7375a839-708e-473a-9c77-4c6b8fc8f879",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain that a reference variable of a superclass type can reference an object of a superclass or subclass type.\n\n**Do This:** Explain the syntax and functionality for creating a 1D array of objects:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Declaring a 1D array of a superclass type can store objects of superclass and subclass types\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Each element in the 1D array is set to `null` if declared and initialized using the `new` keyword\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> A 1D array of objects can be initialized by listing the reference variables in the initializer list\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Each element in the 1D array contains the reference to the instantiated object\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> A 1D array of objects can be initialized by instantiating objects in the initializer list\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate traversing an array of objects and calling the overridden method."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7375a839-708e-473a-9c77-4c6b8fc8f879",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c08ddab8-bdd7-438d-bcc6-0999d74814e2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a7b0c442-a6b8-45f0-9e70-ff46c3a9072b",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5 through 7. Students complete a Check for Understanding, then continue to Level 6 to complete a choice level to create 1D arrays of a superclass type. On Level 7, students complete a choice level to traverse a 1D array of a superclass type and call overridden methods.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Using Polymorphism",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Using Polymorphism",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice level can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of the key terms and creating and using 1D arrays of objects."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a7b0c442-a6b8-45f0-9e70-ff46c3a9072b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c08ddab8-bdd7-438d-bcc6-0999d74814e2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "776b9d7e-bd73-46ea-aa42-8fca47acd460",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *When might we use polymorphism in a program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students note that polymorphism can help make their code more flexible and that they can have a single array to represent multiple types of objects.",
        "name": "Design Thinking",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Prompt students to consider scenarios where they might have a list of a generic type that contains more specific items, such as a grocery list or a playlist containing different music genres. Ask students how polymorphism might make it easier to manage these lists."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "776b9d7e-bd73-46ea-aa42-8fca47acd460",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c2cc854c-4a7c-4b20-9c02-67c189481fa1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bff47061-f6ca-48a8-9671-6eefaecfa265",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 3 Guide includes the Question of the Day and an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to summarize what they have learned and reflect on their progress. Have students respond to these prompts after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and make meaningful connections with the new content."
          }
        ]
