    {
      "key": "5030f323-40d5-40a4-bde1-c66fc74c4038",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You have learned a lot about 1D arrays and software engineering already! Let's take a moment to reflect on and capture what we now know.",
        "name": "Arrays Review",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5030f323-40d5-40a4-bde1-c66fc74c4038",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0828733e-1633-4c84-b345-7fd361274b4e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6d0dde81-6f5e-499e-a344-e471da3ae08a",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to create a concept map in response to the prompt by brainstorming any concepts and ideas that come to mind.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "A concept map helps students illustrate their understanding of the relationships between the concepts they have learned so far. It usually consists of at least two concepts (nouns), a relationship (verb or short description), and an arrow connecting the concepts. This tool allows students to develop stronger connections with the topic and helps them identify what they know and where gaps might exist.\n\nThere is space on the Unit 3 Guide for students to create their concept maps.\n\nYou can also revisit this to have students continue adding to and revising their concept map."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6d0dde81-6f5e-499e-a344-e471da3ae08a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0828733e-1633-4c84-b345-7fd361274b4e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "95f0b022-a467-437c-8ae8-691ed07869af",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students review their brainstorm, identify the concepts that are central to the prompt, and draw arrows to connect the concepts.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to label the arrows with verbs or short descriptions to identify the relationships between the concepts.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students share their concept maps with a neighbor to compare concepts and relationships. Have students add to or revise their concept maps based on their discussions.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The concept map can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of the concepts students have learned so far. This can help determine if any concepts need to be revisited or clarified as you begin the lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "95f0b022-a467-437c-8ae8-691ed07869af",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0828733e-1633-4c84-b345-7fd361274b4e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "48bc43ed-24cf-4e92-b5d6-e46634c0d100",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "48bc43ed-24cf-4e92-b5d6-e46634c0d100",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c0acfdc1-f691-4b30-ba8b-20c01aee77bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "83c58a59-beca-4e71-b413-317aafbf2177",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned in this unit about creating and working with 1D arrays. We have written algorithms to find the sum and average of values in a 1D array, and we can write even more algorithms to search or manipulate values in a 1D array. Today, you will apply what you have learned in this unit to write new algorithms to work with 1D arrays. Before we do, we'll take a look at how we compare `String` objects we might encounter in a dataset.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "83c58a59-beca-4e71-b413-317aafbf2177",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c0acfdc1-f691-4b30-ba8b-20c01aee77bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2a80db60-0405-4514-9317-c97d75b8ab7b",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Comparing String Objects"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2a80db60-0405-4514-9317-c97d75b8ab7b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c0acfdc1-f691-4b30-ba8b-20c01aee77bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "240a4906-71b4-4407-a037-af3c0f9030e6",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that the method returns `false` when two `String` objects containing the same text are compared using `==` but returns `true` when compared using the `equals()` method. Students may wonder why the method returns `false` when both variables refer to the same characters or might wonder about the purpose and functionality of the `equals()` method."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "240a4906-71b4-4407-a037-af3c0f9030e6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c0acfdc1-f691-4b30-ba8b-20c01aee77bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6bbd7147-4643-4971-b165-82d183d71c22",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Comparing and Returning",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Comparing and Returning"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6bbd7147-4643-4971-b165-82d183d71c22",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c0acfdc1-f691-4b30-ba8b-20c01aee77bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "49ddb937-8e5a-4d94-bab8-b1029fc6bbe3",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *When would we want to return inside of a loop? When would we NOT want to return inside of a loop?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students realize that returning inside of a loop will prevent checking the rest of the array, which could result in an incorrect value being returned. Students suggest returning inside of a loop when needing to find the first value that meets the criteria and returning at the end of the method when all values need to be checked.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "49ddb937-8e5a-4d94-bab8-b1029fc6bbe3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c0acfdc1-f691-4b30-ba8b-20c01aee77bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "744e6cfd-b8ef-43f1-add4-50a6d6d54d6b",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Recall that a `String` is an object.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate using the `==` operator to compare two string literals.\n\n**Do This:** Click through the animated slides to explain the Java String Pool:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> A string literal is stored in the Java String Pool\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> A new string literal with the same value points to the existing `String` in the Java String Pool\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Creating a `String` object using the `new` keyword stores the object in heap memory",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Comparing String Objects",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "It is not important for students to understand the specifics about the Java String Pool and heap memory. The goal here is to help students grasp why `String` objects should be compared using the `equals()` method instead of the `==` operator."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "744e6cfd-b8ef-43f1-add4-50a6d6d54d6b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c0acfdc1-f691-4b30-ba8b-20c01aee77bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3aac09f9-5993-41f0-8138-c8e7cc827dfc",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain how the `==` operator is used to compare `String` objects:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Returns `true` if both reference variables point to the same location\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Returns `false` if the reference variables point to different locations\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce comparing `String` objects for equality using the `equals()` method.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students learn about aliases and overriding the `equals()` method to compare objects in a future lesson. The goal here is for students to understand how to compare string literals for equality when writing algorithms with 1D arrays that are of a `String` type."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3aac09f9-5993-41f0-8138-c8e7cc827dfc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c0acfdc1-f691-4b30-ba8b-20c01aee77bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e336ef24-2135-4c2f-86d6-6211e30b3398",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In data science, software engineers aim to use data to find information that they can use to solve meaningful problems. Let's use what we have learned so far about 1D arrays, object-oriented programming, and algorithms to search and manipulate elements.",
        "duration": "25",
        "name": "Array Algorithms",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e336ef24-2135-4c2f-86d6-6211e30b3398",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c0acfdc1-f691-4b30-ba8b-20c01aee77bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e41ca63b-5655-4813-9862-a6626775aee3",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair a copy of the Writing Algorithms with Arrays handout and a set of the Planning Algorithms manipulatives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to work with their partner to write pseudocode for one of the problems.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to use the manipulatives to act out their solution and make adjustments to their algorithm as needed. You could also choose to model using the manipulatives and writing pseudocode for a problem."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e41ca63b-5655-4813-9862-a6626775aee3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c0acfdc1-f691-4b30-ba8b-20c01aee77bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "da0be401-4954-410a-9ea8-5fc9135e4694",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5 and 6. Students complete a Check for Understanding, then continue to Level 6 to implement their algorithm for their chosen problem.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Array Algorithms",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice level can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of the key terms and writing algorithms using 1D arrays."
          },
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "These levels include additional columns from the dataset beyond what is needed to solve the given problem. You can use these to encourage students to implement additional algorithms to explore the dataset further to find information or identify trends."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "da0be401-4954-410a-9ea8-5fc9135e4694",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c0acfdc1-f691-4b30-ba8b-20c01aee77bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b49102e8-1323-40a0-86d1-c2ef1bbf8d6f",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When we write new code, getting feedback from our peers is helpful to make sure we have met the requirements of the problem efficiently.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Code Review",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b49102e8-1323-40a0-86d1-c2ef1bbf8d6f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c0acfdc1-f691-4b30-ba8b-20c01aee77bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d5f9d4ff-4a50-48d6-bf21-de301873802e",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to have students participate in the Code Review Call and Response.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to conduct a code review on their chosen problem.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students may be at different points when it is time for the code review. Emphasize to students that their work does not need to be completed to get feedback. Remind students that the problem-solving and development process is iterative and that receiving feedback from peers while they are working can help give them additional insights, perspectives, and guidance.\n\nConducting code reviews on choice levels is slightly different than on single levels. To conduct a code review on a choice level:\n1. Students select the level they completed to request a code review on their work.\n2. Students return to the options by clicking the bubble at the top of the page.\n3. Students select the level their peers completed to give feedback on their work.\n\nTo review the feedback given on their work, students return to the options by clicking the bubble at the top of the page, then select the level they completed. Students should then review the feedback and make improvements to their code and repeat the process as needed until they are satisfied with their solution."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d5f9d4ff-4a50-48d6-bf21-de301873802e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c0acfdc1-f691-4b30-ba8b-20c01aee77bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "29adad63-1c4b-4560-ab32-ab1d9c5448d2",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Great work today! You have used your skills as software engineers to write new algorithms with 1D arrays and solve problems like a data scientist.",
        "name": "Glows, Grows, Want-to-Knows",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "29adad63-1c4b-4560-ab32-ab1d9c5448d2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ae2bb906-c1c0-468c-9cf4-32b2b9c34800"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "78973ebc-b361-4ef1-9e7c-2edf74b9e752",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What was awesome about writing your code?*\n* *What is one action you can take to improve your code?*\n* *What questions do you have about today?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share their achievements and aspects of their program that they are proud of as well as challenges they overcame and how they solved them. Students may suggest ways they can improve their program, such as decomposing the problem down further or identifying additional preconditions for their algorithms.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Glows, Grows, Want-to-Knows is a strategy to help students identify their strengths and areas of improvement and share any questions or misconceptions."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "78973ebc-b361-4ef1-9e7c-2edf74b9e752",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ae2bb906-c1c0-468c-9cf4-32b2b9c34800"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4cae030d-0f53-4c87-bd59-24a97ac772ea",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 3 Guide includes the Question of the Day and an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to summarize what they have learned and reflect on their progress. Have students respond to these prompts after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and make meaningful connections with the new content."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4cae030d-0f53-4c87-bd59-24a97ac772ea",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ae2bb906-c1c0-468c-9cf4-32b2b9c34800"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6c0b23bd-f49e-4ea7-88db-ac344a86d5e1",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6c0b23bd-f49e-4ea7-88db-ac344a86d5e1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ae2bb906-c1c0-468c-9cf4-32b2b9c34800"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "450b3e38-2cc3-46d7-b16f-17756fe50971",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "450b3e38-2cc3-46d7-b16f-17756fe50971",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ae2bb906-c1c0-468c-9cf4-32b2b9c34800"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e9e54391-9f2b-49c3-8dc4-8a3ab301dc21",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You have learned a lot about how data can be used to find information and answer questions. Computer science and data play a large role in how decisions are made, products are designed, or to make predictions.",
        "name": "Using Data",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e9e54391-9f2b-49c3-8dc4-8a3ab301dc21",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5011f4f4-3bf9-478a-b6f8-595c7a94bcfb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fce053a6-4c52-40db-b664-61fb432e4c37",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the dataset.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What is a question you could answer using this data?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest questions they could answer using this dataset, such as whether high number of hours or specific genres are more likely to improve mental health conditions.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How would you use 1D arrays and algorithms to help you answer these questions?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest storing each column as a 1D array and searching multiple arrays at the same time to find information. Students might also suggest writing algorithms to find all of a specific genre and counting the number of times that genre improves mental health conditions or calculating the average number of hours someone listens to music.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Have students consider their personal interests or topics of interest. Ask students about things they might want to know about these interests or topics and what datasets they might look for to answer these questions."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fce053a6-4c52-40db-b664-61fb432e4c37",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5011f4f4-3bf9-478a-b6f8-595c7a94bcfb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6d21e1be-a5e5-46bf-8ed3-9355af608f2a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6d21e1be-a5e5-46bf-8ed3-9355af608f2a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "737d7eb6-cd93-4e2b-b3cf-27a20f9b005c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a30d6f8a-0cf1-4b20-8ccc-1c28add982ff",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have used loops to traverse a 1D array and combined loops with selection statements to implement algorithms. We can even write a loop inside of another loop! Today, we will explore how nested loops work and how we can use these to develop new algorithms with arrays.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a30d6f8a-0cf1-4b20-8ccc-1c28add982ff",
        "lesson_activity.key": "737d7eb6-cd93-4e2b-b3cf-27a20f9b005c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1bfcea54-2059-4a87-ab3e-82c98c62931a",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Nested Loops"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1bfcea54-2059-4a87-ab3e-82c98c62931a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "737d7eb6-cd93-4e2b-b3cf-27a20f9b005c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "830ab9c4-572a-4351-b920-ec22c1dc90d4",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that the program uses nested loops and that the inner loop is fully executed for each iteration of the outer loop. Students may wonder about other scenarios where nested loops would be useful."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "830ab9c4-572a-4351-b920-ec22c1dc90d4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "737d7eb6-cd93-4e2b-b3cf-27a20f9b005c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9350eaf3-66dc-405a-8275-d4f1683bed38",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Nested Loops*.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Nested Loops",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9350eaf3-66dc-405a-8275-d4f1683bed38",
        "lesson_activity.key": "737d7eb6-cd93-4e2b-b3cf-27a20f9b005c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1611252a-5089-4b54-9491-8317ab35c759",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Nested Loops"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1611252a-5089-4b54-9491-8317ab35c759",
        "lesson_activity.key": "737d7eb6-cd93-4e2b-b3cf-27a20f9b005c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8dc8a171-7896-4195-af20-f3cd439fb747",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***nested loop*** and explain that when a loop is nested inside another loop, the inner loop must complete all its iterations before the outer loop can continue.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate tracing a nested loop.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Model tracing the first two iterations of the loop, then ask students to assist in completing the rest of the trace table."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8dc8a171-7896-4195-af20-f3cd439fb747",
        "lesson_activity.key": "737d7eb6-cd93-4e2b-b3cf-27a20f9b005c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8c7f4d61-e5ea-44d5-ae26-37f840349d76",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students trace the code segment.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain the solution."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8c7f4d61-e5ea-44d5-ae26-37f840349d76",
        "lesson_activity.key": "737d7eb6-cd93-4e2b-b3cf-27a20f9b005c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c881dfcb-fd09-4674-aeda-ee5116a605bd",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Sometimes, we need to evaluate our data for situations like invalid or duplicate values. Duplicate values could change the meaning of the data or tell us about things like the popularity of a certain element. Finding duplicates is another standard algorithm that can be applied to many scenarios.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Finding Duplicates",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c881dfcb-fd09-4674-aeda-ee5116a605bd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "737d7eb6-cd93-4e2b-b3cf-27a20f9b005c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "eb999135-b1b3-459b-98c6-445c68093c88",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair a copy of the Finding Duplicates handout and a set of the Planning Algorithms Manipulatives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to work with their partner to write pseudocode for one of the problems.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to use the manipulatives to act out their solution and make adjustments to their algorithm as needed. You could also choose to model using the manipulatives and writing pseudocode for a problem."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "eb999135-b1b3-459b-98c6-445c68093c88",
