    {
      "key": "5ae5a247-f4d7-4a59-8222-4a041e466c3b",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5ae5a247-f4d7-4a59-8222-4a041e466c3b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "989b3e21-49ba-4c16-b68c-86ef7cd8881f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "434345a4-ef89-434c-86b1-b1d22b0f8948",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The unit assessment project assesses proficiency in the knowledge and skills developed in this unit. It is completed in three class periods to plan and create the program, including reading and analyzing data. Students participate in planning and feedback activities to solve problems, reinforce software development practices and self-image as software engineers, and improve their programs.\n\nIf there is not enough time for the three-day project, a one-day option achieves the targeted learning objectives and goals. If using this option, refer to the [**Data for Social Good Project 1-Day Lesson Plan**](https://studio.code.org/s/csa3-2023/lessons/14). While the one-day option covers the learning objectives and goals, it shortens planning and reflection time. Consider this tradeoff when deciding which version to use."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "434345a4-ef89-434c-86b1-b1d22b0f8948",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2c7ece6b-da83-4f27-a20b-9a5db807a7a3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "19f90ceb-cb67-44e0-ad58-333180504c43",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Many industries rely on data to identify solutions to problems and make decisions. Each user has different needs based on the information they need and the questions they need to answer.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Warm Up",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "19f90ceb-cb67-44e0-ad58-333180504c43",
        "lesson_activity.key": "13b48f71-2de1-47ef-8362-d27f3782cd89"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d0194efb-7443-4834-85bb-6ccae005d3a4",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Show the examples of different types of users and their data needs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What does this make you wonder about how you could create a data analysis program for a user?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students talk about obtaining data related to a user's needs and reading the data into a program. Students present ideas of questions the user might have and algorithms that can find the answers to these questions and how users would interact with the program to choose the information they need."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d0194efb-7443-4834-85bb-6ccae005d3a4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "13b48f71-2de1-47ef-8362-d27f3782cd89"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "094f8bbe-2cbc-4920-b5d1-f29b0a441d7b",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Over the next few days, you will be developing a program to store and analyze data from a text file similar to the programs we have worked with throughout the unit. You will need to store data from a text file in a 1D array and apply algorithms to process and analyze the data.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Brainstorming and Planning",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "094f8bbe-2cbc-4920-b5d1-f29b0a441d7b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "13b48f71-2de1-47ef-8362-d27f3782cd89"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c8628d2d-7258-488a-832e-f620d22acc72",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Data for Social Good Project Planning Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the project requirements.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to read the rubric on pages 2 and 3.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do you notice about the project requirements and rubric? What does success look like for this project?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share what they notice about the project requirements and rubric and identify the components to implement in their program.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What barriers do you anticipate to achieving success on this project?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students identify barriers they anticipate and share any questions they have about the project.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c8628d2d-7258-488a-832e-f620d22acc72",
        "lesson_activity.key": "13b48f71-2de1-47ef-8362-d27f3782cd89"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d1aee362-b1ff-4956-ae0b-6cc06c3ce019",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Introduce the steps students will take each day to complete the project:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Day 1 steps\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Day 2 steps\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Day 3 steps"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d1aee362-b1ff-4956-ae0b-6cc06c3ce019",
        "lesson_activity.key": "13b48f71-2de1-47ef-8362-d27f3782cd89"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d639abdb-71d4-42a6-9d6a-cc2f31f36f8e",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Before you begin writing your program, you first need to choose your topic, plan how you will organize your program and data, and identify the questions you want to answer about your data.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d639abdb-71d4-42a6-9d6a-cc2f31f36f8e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "13b48f71-2de1-47ef-8362-d27f3782cd89"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ff647d64-602c-4aac-92ad-93d64bf470f7",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Introduce the user scenarios for the project:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Streaming music customer, avian veterinary student, technology non-profit manager\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Community activist, advertising specialist, choose your own",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students can also create their own rather than using one of the provided scenarios."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ff647d64-602c-4aac-92ad-93d64bf470f7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "13b48f71-2de1-47ef-8362-d27f3782cd89"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fd37d84e-2985-4e04-8102-97cfb0ea49b7",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to identify their topic of interest, create UML diagrams for their classes, and identify the questions they want to answer on the Data for Social Good Project Planning Guide.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The classes for each user scenario are created on the corresponding choice level. Have students look at the data sets and files for their selected user stories as they plan their program."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fd37d84e-2985-4e04-8102-97cfb0ea49b7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "13b48f71-2de1-47ef-8362-d27f3782cd89"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c380a666-4609-438b-bdae-b6869439dcb9",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to develop their Data for Social Good Project.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Development",
        "progression_name": "Data for Social Good Project"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c380a666-4609-438b-bdae-b6869439dcb9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "13b48f71-2de1-47ef-8362-d27f3782cd89"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9e0a47fc-e871-4a4d-b1d7-b4f187378d05",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "This is a good time to commit our code and save our new superclass and subclasses to the Backpack. Anytime we make changes to our programs, it is helpful to commit, or save, our work as a new version in case we need to revert to a previous version.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9e0a47fc-e871-4a4d-b1d7-b4f187378d05",
        "lesson_activity.key": "13b48f71-2de1-47ef-8362-d27f3782cd89"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9d4130e0-d51e-4a5c-b6f2-8443636ccb65",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Play the music clip to cue committing their code and saving their classes to the Backpack.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Using music to cue transitions helps create routines in the classroom. When students hear cues, they know it is time to transition to a specific activity. Emphasize to students what the music clip means, and be consistent with the use of the music clip to cue the activity.\n\nClick the blue play icon on the slide to play the music cue."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9d4130e0-d51e-4a5c-b6f2-8443636ccb65",
        "lesson_activity.key": "13b48f71-2de1-47ef-8362-d27f3782cd89"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4fe56261-00b6-4768-95b8-e7d57579ea53",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You made a lot of progress on your project today! Let's take a moment to reflect on what you have accomplished so far and what you need to focus on next.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Wrap Up",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4fe56261-00b6-4768-95b8-e7d57579ea53",
        "lesson_activity.key": "13b48f71-2de1-47ef-8362-d27f3782cd89"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7853f6ac-7749-4233-992d-c78e90646879",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to respond to the Day 1 Reflection prompt on the Data for Social Good Project Planning Guide.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, have students share their thoughts and ideas with a neighbor."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "You can use the Day 1 Reflection as an optional completion assessment."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
